03913nam a22005895i 9780300240542DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20192019ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002405427 a10.12987/97803002405422doi  a(DE-B1597)521962  a(OCoLC)1083671074  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDA505 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a941.072231 aVaughn, James M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Empire at the Accession of George III :bThe East India Company and the Crisis and Transformation of Britain's Imperial State /cJames M. Vaughn. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Lewis Walpole Series in Eighteenth-Century Culture and History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn important revisionist history that casts eighteenth-century British politics and imperial expansion in a new light. In this bold debut work, historian James M. Vaughn challenges the scholarly consensus that British India and the Second Empire were founded "in a fit of absence of mind." He instead argues that the origins of the Raj and the largest empire of the modern world were rooted in political conflicts and movements in Britain. It was British conservatives who shaped the Second Empire into one of conquest and dominion, emphasizing the extraction of resources and the subjugation of colonial populations.   Drawing on a wide array of sources, Vaughn shows how the East India Company was transformed from a corporation into an imperial power in the service of British political forces opposed to the rising radicalism of the period. The Company's dominion in Bengal, where it raised territorial revenue and maintained a large army, was an autocratic bulwark of Britain's established order. A major work of political and imperial history, this volume offers an important new understanding of the era and its global ramifications.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065488240uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300240542?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300240542423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300240542/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065488-2  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2019  aZDB-23-DGGb2019